segments.text: warm up here.
There is something else I want to ask you about that has a good deal to do with your father and his activities.
I noticed on a map of Texas today that the Old Dolores settlement has been made into something.
Is it a national or a state?
It is recognized as a state historical site.
Now, is this the Rancho Dolores or the Old Hacienda?
It's the old hacienda.
The old hacienda.
Which, by the way, it was the very, very first settlement in the 1700s here in the United States, or one of the first ones.
If you will read the book that my father co-authored.
I have.
And he mentions that particularly.
Which is true.
That was even, the old, the lot of settlement was settled even before signing Nassau and any of the, definitely even before Laredo.
That was in the 1750s.
It was 1750, Jose Vasquez Borrego.
That is correct.
Well, then later, your grandfather, I believe it was, no, your great-grandfather, Cosme Martinez, founded the Rancho Dolores.
That's correct.
Which was, what, a few miles from the Hacienda?
How far is it from the Hacienda?
Well, exactly the distance, I really don't know.

but it just relatively i would say it's a short period of time i mean short distance up the road up the road yeah not not by by today's standards well whatever happened to that settlement's no longer lived in uh no it is still you might consider it a ghost settlement now but you still have many of the old
walls and old building sites.
They're still there.
Whatever happened to that settlement?
Has it ever been set aside?
It is owned by the family.
And in this case, it belongs to Antonio Martinez and Jose Maria Martinez, who presently live in San Antonio.
By the way, Antonio Martinez died, so it's Jose Maria Martinez and other sisters.
Are there any children?
I'm afraid not.
No.
So there will be some.
They have nephews and nieces, and more than likely they will probably be the ones that eventually die.
Well, I understand there was a little bit of controversy with the Vidauris over this.
The Vidauris, that's correct.
As a matter of fact, it was the oldest case in the 49th District Court.
And just about a little better than two years ago, that case was finally settled.

and it was settled in favor of the well how was it set because partially part part of the of that track was was uh settled in favor of the vidaris and the other part in favor of the martinez but here again my father was the one that was uh most influential by the testimony that he provided so yeah because it was in court for a long time it was in court for a better a little better than 40 years
And during this period of time, I would say far more money was spent than the actual value of that acreage.
This is not uncommon.
No, that's true.
Well, I wondered what had happened to it, because I believe the last thing I saw was
in about, I guess, in the early 1960s.
It was still in litigation.
That is correct.
So it's finally completely out of the courts.
It's finally completely out of the courts.
It's been compromised.
It's finally settled by the 49 District Court.
Judge E.J.
Gason presiding.
I believe Robert Lee Bobbitt had made the suggestion back in about 1961 or so that it be turned over to the state of Texas as a state park.
And I wondered if anything had ever
No, nothing along those lines.
That never happened.
It would be nice if something like that would be done.
And let's hope that someday it will.
But that's going to now be in the hands of the nieces and nephews and families that live in San Antonio.
That is correct.
That is correct.
Oh, by the way, whatever happened to Robert Lee Bobbitt?
Is he still alive?
He died last year.
Last year.
A little better than a year ago.
And...
This was after his wife died, a little later on in the death.
And his son, Robert Lee Wilder Jr., is in practice, has a law practice in San Antonio.

Was this an ongoing part of the Hicks, Hicks, Dixon, and Bobbitt firm, or did it finally just... No, it finally was dissolved, which many of the papers my father still, or still have over at the ranch.
And part of it are placed over at the Texina archives.
Which, by the way, that has a lot of history there, too.
Yes, it does.
Because there were many that the law firm for the South Texas area was this law firm of Hicks, Hicks, Dixon, and Bobbitt.
And many land.

cases were handled through this firm and they were the ones that settled quite a number and there's considerable amount of of information in land matters and land titles which are within these files so there's tremendous amount of of original
or primary data or primary source information.
There's one I'd like to ask you about.
It was a big, thick file.
Do you know anything about the Perdernal?
Perdernal?
Yeah.
in Grant down in South Zapata County.
Well, no, I'm afraid I'm not that well versed with it, so I think I better let it alone.
Well, I know what happened to it up to 1921.
I just wondered if it's still in existence as an entity at all.
I'm afraid I don't know.
You don't know.
I'll ask around when I get to Zapata.
You might ask Judge Bravo.
Judge Bravo would probably know.
Well, I'd like to ask a little bit more about your mother.
Well, let's see.
She was born in the 1890s, wasn't she?
Yes, ma'am.
That's correct.
When did she die?
She died six months after my father did.
After your father.
And she, like I mentioned before, she was born in Old Guerrero, Tamaulipas, Mexico.
His father was a merchant by the name of Tomas Trevio.
And Don Tomas, again, died.
He was in his 80s at the time, I understand, when he died.
And my mother married twice prior to my father.
And he lived in, after she moved from Guerrero, she lived in Olzapata.
And from there, she came down to Laredo when he married my father.
Do you know when she moved to Old Zapata?
I'm afraid I couldn't tell you.
That's the thing about it, though, that my mother was, she really did not have the historical interest that my father had.
And consequently, there were many things that were left unanswered, you might say.
Well, was this fairly typical of women of her generation?
That's right.
That's right.
She was the type that, you know, more or less was rather reserved, rather quiet, and would stay in the background, this type of attitude.
Again, the Spanish influence, the Mexican attitude.
But there was a woman in your family who was apparently not at all like that, the mother of Blas Maria Uribe.
All right, that's Doa Jesusita.
Doa Jesusita, who came from Guerrero after she was widowed with two young sons.
No, that's Blas Maria Uribe.
Doa Jesusita was his daughter.
Was his daughter, that's right, who was my father's mother.
But I'm talking about Blas Maria's mother.
Do you remember any family stories about her?
She's the one that came with two sons, a widow, apparently a fairly young woman, crossed the river and went to live in, do you call it Uribeo?
Uribeo.
Uribeo.
Uribeo.
That's right.
A very strong-willed woman.
That is correct.
And she was the one that initially was responsible for that particular settlement.
Now she actually founded it herself.
Well, to a great extent.
And her sons weren't old enough to be much help.
No, they were very much still in diapers, so I hear, or so I was told.
Have you ever heard any explanation for the kind of woman she was for that day and time?
I'm afraid not.
I would say that here you would have to go to some of the Uribe's
And we get a little bit more information in that area.
By the way, mentioning Uribe's, there's a man by the name of Derli Uribe, whose son, Jorge Uribe, has made a family tree on the Uribe site.
And this family tree dates back to 200 years, to the 1770s.
And it's a good-sized wall.
And in this particular family tree, he traces it all the way through and includes, wherever possible, not only the date of birth, but the date of death, and all the children that follow thereafter.
And he has been able to trace it through one generation beyond the Uribes.
For instance, my father was a Martinez Uribe.
So he traced it on through my generation.
And that's where he stops.
Now, how did he derive his interest in genealogy?
Or do you know that?
Again, because of the family.
Well, now, you talk to people, and this is true.
both in Mexico and in the United States.
And you talk to a great many people, and they don't know who their family is beyond their grandparents.
And then ever so often, you find a family where this interest in genealogy just goes all the way back.
It's true of my mother's family in Charleston that I was telling you about.
They go back.
They take the march all the way across Kentucky and the whole thing.
Now, just from your observations, why do you think your family has retained this kind of interest?
Can you think of any reason when a lot of other families don't?
Well, I would imagine the reason why is because we are one of the descendants of the original settlers.
And normally this, I guess, this interest stays with the family all along.
which was the case with the original settlers in Old Dolores and in San Ignacio.
That's also true of my family, interestingly.
They were the original settlers of Charleston, Missouri, and little towns in that area.
And this is the reason, I guess, why you have that interest.
You can't help but be proud of the fact that your family, somewhere down the line, was responsible for a settlement.
And in this case, our family was responsible for a settlement in the 1700s.
And when my great-great-grandfather got this land, which was deeded by the king of Spain, he originally got a little better than 200,000 acres of land.
And naturally by all the...
This is Jesus.
Don Jesus.
Don Jesus.
That's right.
He actually bought it from the heirs of Borrego.
Borrego.
Borrego, yeah.
And then that deed was from the king of Spain.
From the king of Spain.
And so this, again, is probably the reason why we always have a tendency to be proud of it and make sure that we do have that family history or the family tree or the family background.
Well, one thing I've suspected myself,
collecting these genealogies, and I'm sort of speculating on tape.
But in every case that I've found this extensive knowledge of family, it has been landed families.
And I just wonder if this might have something to do with it, a need to keep track of the land.
That very well possibly would be.
I suppose you still have lands in Zapata County and cousins with lands.
That's great.
What about cousin marriage?
You say your mother and father were first cousins.
What about your mother and father?
I'm sorry, your father's first and second wives were his first cousins.
That is correct.
They were first cousins.
Was this common?
Very common.
And again, we come back again to the principle that they did not want the land to be divested with any greater number of people that were considered outsiders.
Again, that's a feeling.
They wanted to keep the land within a certain group or a certain family and try to keep as many other people to have an interest in it.
So I guess that's the reason primarily why we come back again to the same, why cousins married cousins, even though they were first cousins, which was the case with my father.
Well, I had an explanation.
given to me by one of my relatives, which was a strong suspicion that they only thought that cousins were good enough for them.
Because again, the patterning is there.
The tremendous amount of cousin marriage, I think, was primarily third cousin
Second and third cousin marriage, but it was still generation after generation of cousin marriage.
So this is quite prevalent, very strong.
But it's, again, something that tends to be found in, I think, settling families who have land.
I still have a number of cousins.
that are married to cousins.
And if you will go to San Ignacio and ask, and you will find most of the Uribe's are married to Uribe's, are Martinez and Uribe's, but they're all cousins.
Now your wife, is she any kind at all?
No.
What is her name?
Ancita.
Ancita.
But I must say though that
During my adolescent period, my father tried to instill this into me, which I don't think I ever paid too much attention.
But he kept on.
He was the most instrumental.
The fact that he was retired, he had a considerable amount of time.
And he was very influential, because I always felt very close to my father, even though there was considerable difference in ages.
How old was he when you were born?
He was 60 when I was born.
Really quite old.
Did he ever talk to you about what it meant to him to have children so late in life?
Oh, yes.
He was extremely proud.
He was extremely proud of me.
And he always had more than enough time for me.
And everywhere he went, I always tagged along, or he would always make it a point to bring me along.
And it was all during this time that he would try to,
He used his philosophy on me.
But I'm afraid that particular philosophy never works.
I try to stay within the family.
I dated a seventh cousin.
That didn't work either.
His philosophy, what do you think his philosophy was, if you were to talk about his philosophy of life?
He was a man that had a lot of foresight.
He was quite optimistic.
And he definitely was an aggressive man as far as his ability and initiative to do things.
And even though he was small in stature, he definitely was tall or big in attitude and ideas.
the manner in which he himself believed in the future.
And the fact remains that he was, I would say, one of the first ones, if not the first one, to have a formal education and still come back to his original town.
Did any of his brothers and sisters go to college?
The youngest brother went to college, but he never graduated.
Did your father have anything to do with that?
Yes.
He was the one that paid for his schooling.
He would send them also to St. Edward's.
And he was out there for about a year and a half.
But that youngest brother was a processor.
He died before my father did.
Processo, did he ever marry?
No, he never did.
Well, that's something I'm a little curious about.
Maybe you could enlighten me.
I've noticed in the genealogies in your father's papers that there are a great many people who
didn't marry and particularly I would say in the generation that was about your father's age.
There would be families of five to ten children or more and maybe one or two of them would marry.
Do you have any idea why this particular phenomena?
I don't know.
I can only speculate.

And what I can speculate is this, that we come back again to this business of if one of the family would be dating somebody that did not belong, let's say, to the family, which again is part of the cousin thing, probably they would frown on him.
And if there wasn't a cousin good enough to marry, then they definitely wouldn't marry, or at least
their parents would be influential enough not to let them marry.
I guess, now again, this is speculation on my part.
Well, I'm not sure.
I'd have to, you know, take it to the computer or something, but I think that

I think there was a much higher percentage of children, and I'm thinking about some of the other genealogies your father collected that were other families along the river, that back say in the 1700s and 1800s that most of the children did marry.
for the most part, but that it was in this generation of the late 1900s that there started being so many people who didn't marry.
Now, like I say, this is just impressionistic.
I can't show you statistics on it.
And I wonder if anything happened at that time in addition to this family thing that would have limited the number of people getting married.
I wish I could give you some background there, but I'm afraid I don't have any.
Well, I've speculated, too.
I've wondered about the land being subdivided, say, one time too many or something.
But you'd never heard anything spoken to this effect.
No.
That's a good question.
Well, it was an interesting thing.
I looked at it and wondered if there was any real reason.
Because I had a few, I call them uncles, which were first cousins of my father that didn't marry.
And they definitely had accumulated considerable wealth, but yet they didn't have any children in which they would leave other than nephews and nieces.
So the land that they accumulated then would go to the nephews and nieces.
That is correct.
And be subdivided.
Right.
Now, the situation now, there are very many families that have very large holdings.
Are most of the holdings fairly small by this time?
By this time, especially in that area, they are relatively small.
The only ones that are large, and we come back now to a different area.
We come here now to Webb County, and that's a Benavides family, the Doa Rosa Benavides.
They own upwards of 100,000 acres of land.
And that is land that has been inherited over the years.
And right now, she has two grandsons, one by the name of Carlos Y. Benavidez Jr. and the other one, Arturo N. Benavidez.
And this is about the largest,
acreage that I can think of that has been deeded over a period of generations.
But as far as from my family, most of the acreage, the greatest number I would say is about, you'd think in terms of 10 or 12,000, possibly at the most 15,000 acres of land.
I inherited a little better, just right around 4,000, which I consider small by our standards.
Well, let's consider it by how many cattle you can graze on it.
How many cattle can you run on 4,000 acres of Zapata County land?
Well, again, we come back again to how well improved the acreage is.
If it's open land, grazing land,
then you think in terms of 20 to 25 acres per head.

If you have highly improved land that's root plowed, seeded either with buffelgrass or something along that line, and has plenty of water, well, then you definitely cut down tremendously as to the number of acres that you need per head.
In other words, it takes a pretty high capital input on this land to do much with it.
That's right.
Well, now, the land itself, from old family stories, do you have any idea what it was like in terms of vegetation when the first settlers, well, say, when Jesus Trevino came in 1830?
It was very hard, very, very hard.
And this is the reason, too, why, again...
Very hard.
In the sense that, I mean, here you did not have the type of...
this was more arid land.
That's what I'm thinking of.
A land that did not have too much water.

And again, that's the reason why whenever they would have partition deeds on some of this acreage, they would always make it a point that they would have a lane that would lead all the way down to the river just to make sure that there would be direct access to water.
by the same reason.
So this was very arid land.
Now, today the things are very different because we have Falcon Lake on one end and then Amistad Dam on the other.
And these two great bodies of water have provided a greater
humidity in the atmosphere, which brings in more rain.
You've really got the meteorological records on this.
It's actually been raining more.
Yes ma'am, that's right.
And we didn't have this then, or they didn't have this.
So definitely the country here was drier and the rains were few and far between.
And you had to make sure that there would be some access to water.
And this is the reason why you have many of these, all of the land grants and all of the partitions, they start at the river and go east from there.
Just making sure that all of them have direct access to the Rio Grande.
Do you know how big the original pociones were?
The original Porciones, I understand.
Well, you're asking me now something I knew but I forgot.
But they were very, very large.
Well, on the map, just by measuring it, I calculated they must be about a mile wide and about 11 miles deep.
But I was just measuring on the map.
Does that sound about right?
Well, they were about or probably a little wider than that.
A little wider than a mile.
That's right.
That's right.
And something like 11 miles.
Something like that.
That's correct.
Because they really went in further deep from the river.
Very, very deep.
And then the lands beyond that, beyond the Porcionis, when did they start being parceled out, or do you know?
I'm afraid I don't have any idea.
You're asking an individual that does not have that much of a background in history as my father did, which is bad.
I realize that.
I wish I had... Well, I'm asking you every question I can think of right now that has popped into my mind, and you know a lot of them you've answered beautifully, so I might as well keep on asking.
Fine.
Well, let's see, the Porciones, they were the Webb County or the Porciones of Laredo, and then there was the big Jos Vzquez Borrego.
The Jos Vzquez Borrego grant was divided into...
the San Ignacio subdivision, the Dolores subdivision, and the Corralito subdivision.
And they were bigger than Porciones.
Very much so.
Very much.
That's right.
And the land down there, one thing I did wonder about was the vegetation.
Has it changed any since Falcon Dam went in?
Yes.
You now are able to see quite a bit of green in that area that used to be very arid.
And, of course, the improvements that have been made now by bringing in buffled grass, which is a new type of grass that was introduced not too many years ago.
Well, what about the irrigation rights?
For a time, it looked like, from some of the newspaper articles in your father's paper, that they weren't going to get any irrigation rights.
Was this changed?
Did they get irrigation rights from these?
Well, yes, but only those people that were using.
the river for irrigation.
The people that did not use or didn't have it, any uses and were not able to prove that they used it over a period of years, they lost their water rights.
So this is a case.
Now what was the justification for them losing the water rights since that was one of the things that the dam was built for?
Well, this was a ruling of the Texas Water Commission, and that's the reason why the Texas Water Commission was created, to supervise the irrigation and the usage of water usage.
And those people that never took advantage of these water rights prior to the dam and did not set up any kind of
How should I say it?
Irrigation?
Irrigation system.
They simply did not, simply lost their water rights.
Excuse me.
Yes, sir.
Can I just, let me just interrupt one second.
I'm trying to find a book here.
Sure.
Right here.
Oh, that's all right, Harry.
Thank you.
Well, did your father have anything to do with helping people establish their irrigation rights?
Not that much.
I'm afraid that this was finally settled not too long ago, after my father had died.
We must keep in mind that this is a relatively new agency that was created just several years ago.
But at the time, it was a hot issue that was
were originally brought by the people from the valley.
They were the ones that initially started this litigation.
Well, was this applied in the valley, too?
This rule was applied also in the valley.
Was there any particular group of people that lost out more than any others on this?
Not that I'm aware of.
It just was sort of a catch-as-catch-can kind of thing.
That's right.
That's very interesting.
About the tourism aspects, your father spent a lot of time guiding people down to San Ignacio and this sort of thing.
How did he happen to develop his interest in history?

his well he initially acquired it uh through the interest that he had from from his own father who by the way was was used quite extensively as a witness again to settle land titles uh i know that mr he would relate a number of occasions where mr robert lee bobbitt
would use him as a principal witness, would use my grandfather as a principal witness.
And this was part of the influence, I would imagine, where he acquired.
And he spent a considerable period of time in reviewing the local folklore and the local history.
Local folklore.
Now, there was very little in your father's papers that I would call folklore.
It was pretty much, you know, history.
And even in the book, The Kingdom of Zapata, it was primarily history rather than what I would call folklore.
What, in your opinion, is some of the folklore of the region?
Well, how could I explain that?
I don't know whether some of the writings that you see that... See, my father was a musician, and he really was a musician at heart.
And over time and again, my grandfather would make sure that his sons, who one of them, of course, my father used to...
play the violin.
His other brother, Elgosio, used to play the guitar, and his third brother used to play the accordion.
And my grandfather would always take them along to the different ranches in order to make these violins.
And all the people from the surrounding area would be invited.
this would bring in the atmosphere.
And there was a number of ocurridos that would be, how should I say, composed during that time, especially more so during periods where political activity was very high.
there's a number of versos or verses that relate to some of these political eras or periods.
And this is part of the, anyway.
This is part of the tradition of keeping local history in the area, isn't it?
And at the bailes, what kind of music do they play?
What kind of music?
From waltzes?
to a great extent.
And we used to call them ,, which are get your partner, you know, and swing around.
Like square dances.
Square dance.
Except that they used to refer to them as .
And again, you know, actual
The kind of a song that used to be normally, as a general rule, had some history behind it.
I mean, it had some story to tell.
This, to him, was one area that he always loved, he always enjoyed.
And up to the time of his death, he always, every once in a while, would get his guitar
strum a few pieces of songs that he used to sing way back when.
And he always made it quite interesting.
So he kept his interest in music all of his life?
Oh, all the time, all the time.
Did you ever learn to play?
I'm afraid not.
The bailes, were these, are they still held?
I don't know.
I really don't think so, other than in the towns, but not the way they were held, which were in the ranchos.
And especially more so, like I say, when we go back to the time when a political year
was high, and they would try to bring in, they would bring in the people by this by list, and then this is how they would draw in the people and the votes.
And then from there, they'd take them over to go in and vote.
To the polls.
Hey, that's a painless way to do things.
That's right.
Well, now, the politics of the area, was it pretty much controlled locally in Zapata County, or was it pretty tied in with Webb County?
No, it was pretty much controlled in Zapata County.
In Zapata County.
And this is part of the reason, too, why they call it the Kingdom of Zapata, because of politics.
It was pretty controlled.
And it was during the era of A.P.
Spahn.
Yeah.
What kind of man was he?
Well, he was another George Barr, so I understand.
What kind of man was Judge Parr?
He's the one that controlled the politics of that area, and nothing could be done unless he had say-so there.
Well, would you call him a benevolent or a non-benevolent dictator then?
I would say he's benevolent.
But still, dictator wouldn't be an inappropriate word?
I don't know, because I, to some degree, believe in all those things.
I was raised in that philosophy.
Oh, yeah, okay.
In other words, a strong figure.
A strong figure.
An authoritarian figure.
An authoritarian figure.
Well, was he, would you have called him a good man?
I would imagine, based on my father's comments, I think he was a good man.
How did Spohn, now where was he from originally?
Well, he came up from the east.
Is that a German name?
I think it is a German name.
And how did he get there?
He married a local lady there.
And that's how he got involved in local politics.
And he was one of the few people that spoke English.
I presume he also learned Spanish.
Oh, very much so.
But his ability to speak English was, I suppose, an asset.
Well, now say up to 1900, how many people in Zapata County spoke English?
Very few.
Very few.
and say, when did English become, or is it?
How many people are there now who don't speak English?
Oh, there's a lot of people that don't speak English.
And like I say, the Mexican-American is very predominant in this area.
What about the schools?
Is Spanish taught in the schools, too?
It is taught in the schools, and the problem is that it's spoken.
more so than English is.
And it's a problem because they don't get to practice the English the way they should.
But they do learn to read and write Spanish.
Well, that's my understanding.
I learned to read and write strictly to a great extent at the beginning on my own.
Then I took a course or two, but really not that much of a formal education.
Well, it's not taught in the younger grades then.
It is now being taught.
It is now.
But when you were going to school, it wasn't.
It wasn't.
Now the bilingual program is very strong, quite predominant now.
And the emphasis is there.
So many of these students are now being taught in both languages, which is good.
Oh, heaven, yes.
Why have to wait until you get to college and go into your first Spanish class?
Yeah, now this is something that I think is interesting, that there was an educational system in Zapata County very early, but it was predominantly Spanish.
And your father was a teacher there.
He was for about, like I said, for several years before he went ranch town into other areas.
What made politics such a, how would you say, a fierce sort of thing in the area?
There were, I would imagine, different groups that wanted to have control.
But if everybody was kin, were these partly family feuds?
That's right.
To some degree, they were family feuds.
That's a problem even nowadays in Zapata County, that you have basically one cousin running against another cousin.
And the bad part about it is that they take it quite personally, and then they don't talk to each other.
That sounds like Charleston again.
Well, it's still predominant.
It's still very predominant.
So this actually creates dissension between families.
When you get family lines, then, that are on opposite political sides.
Very similar place.
No wonder you acquired a considerable interest in our local history.
